#. type: Title #
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:12
#, no-wrap
msgid "How to Install & Use OliveTin on Rocky Linux"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:17
msgid "Have you ever gotten tired of typing in the same CLI commands over and over again? Have you ever wanted everyone else in your house to be able to restart the Plex server without your intervention? Do you want to just type in a name in a web panel, push a button, and watch a customized Docker/LXD container magically appear?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:19
msgid "Then you might want to check out OliveTin. OliveTin is literally just an app that lets you generate a web page from a configuration file, and that web page has buttons. Push the buttons, and OliveTin will run preset bash commands that you set up yourself."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:21
msgid "Sure, you could technically create something like this yourself, from scratch, with enough programming experience... but this is *way* easier. It looks a little something like this when set up (image courtesy of the [OliveTin repository](https://github.com/OliveTin/OliveTin)):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:23
msgid "![A screenshot of OliveTin on the desktop; it features several squares in a grid, with labels and actions for each command that can be run.](olivetin/screenshotDesktop.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:25
msgid "!!! Warning \"NEVER run this app on a public server\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This app is, by design and the creator's own admission, meant to be used on local networks, *maybe* on dev setups. However, it has no user authentication system at present, and (until the developer fixes this) *runs as root by default*.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "    So yeah, use this all you want on a secured and firewalled network. *Don't* put it on anything meant to be used by the public. For now.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "Prerequisites and assumptions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:33
msgid "To follow this guide you will need:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:38
msgid "A minimal amount of comfort or experience with the command line."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:38
msgid "Root access, or the ability to use `sudo`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:38
msgid "To learn the basics of YAML. It is not hard; you'll get the hang of it down below."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing OliveTin"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:42
msgid "OliveTin includes pre-built RPMs. Just download the latest release here for your architecture, and install it. If you're following this guide on a workstation with a graphical desktop, just download the file and double click on it in your file manager of choice."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:44
msgid "If you're installing this app on a server, then you can download it on your work machine and upload it via SSH/SCP/SFTP, or do the thing some people say not to do, and download it with `wget`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:46
msgid "e.g."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "wget https://github.com/OliveTin/OliveTin/releases/download/2022-04-07/OliveTin_2022-04-07_linux_amd64.rpm\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:52
msgid "Then install the app with (again, for example):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "sudo rpm -i OliveTin_2022-04-07_linux_amd64.rpm\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:58
msgid "OliveTin can run as a normal `systemd` service, but do not enable it just yet. You need to set up your configuration file first."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:62
#, no-wrap
msgid "    After some testing, I have determined that these same install instructions will work just fine in a Rocky Linux LXD container. For anyone who likes Docker, pre-built images are available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring OliveTin Actions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:66
msgid "OliveTin can do anything bash can do, and more. You can use it to run apps with CLI options, run bash scripts, restart services, and so on. To get started, open up the configuration file with the text editor of your choice with root/sudo:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "sudo nano /etc/OliveTin/config.yaml\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:72
msgid "The most basic kind of action is a button; you click it, and the command is run on the host computer. You can define it in the YAML file like so:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (yaml)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "actions:\n"
"  - title: Restart Nginx\n"
"    shell: systemctl restart nginx\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:80
msgid "You can also add custom icons to every action like with unicode emoji:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (yaml)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:81
#, no-wrap
msgid "actions:\n"
"  - title: Restart Nginx\n"
"    icon: \"&#1F504\"\n"
"    shell: systemctl restart nginx\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:89
msgid "I'm not going to go into every detail of the customization options, but you can also use text inputs and dropdown menus to add variables and options to the commands you want to run. If you do, OliveTin will prompt you for input before the command is run."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:91
msgid "Doing this, you can run any program, control remote machines with SSH, trigger webhooks, and more. Check out [the official documentation](https://docs.olivetin.app/actions.html) for more ideas."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:93
msgid "But here's an example of my own: I have a personal script that I use to generate LXD containers with web servers pre-installed on them. With OliveTin, I was able to quickly make a GUI for said script like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (yaml)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "actions:\n"
"- title: Build Container\n"
"  shell: sh /home/ezequiel/server-scripts/rocky-host/buildcontainer -c {{ containerName }} -d {{ domainName }} {{ softwarePackage }}\n"
"  timeout: 60\n"
"  arguments:\n"
"    - name: containerName\n"
"      title: Container Name\n"
"      type: ascii_identifier\n\n"
"    - name: domainName\n"
"      title: Domain\n"
"      type: ascii_identifier\n\n"
"    - name: softwarePackage\n"
"      title: Default Software\n"
"      choices:\n"
"        - title: None\n"
"          value:\n\n"
"        - title: Nginx\n"
"          value: -s nginx\n\n"
"        - title: Nginx & PHP\n"
"          value: -s nginx-php\n\n"
"        - title: mariadb\n"
"          value: -s mariadb\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:125
msgid "On the front end, that looks like this (and yes, OliveTin has a dark mode, and I *really* need to change that icon):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:127
msgid "![A form with three text inputs and a dropdown menu](olivetin/containeraction.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:128
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling OliveTin"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:131
msgid "Once you have your configuration file built the way you want it, just enable and start OliveTin with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:132
#, no-wrap
msgid "sudo systemctl enable --now OliveTin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:137
msgid "Every time you edit the configuration file, you'll need to restart the service in the usual way:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:138
#, no-wrap
msgid "sudo systemctl restart OliveTin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:145
msgid "OliveTin is a pretty great way to run everything from a bash commands to some fairly complex operations with scripts. Remember, that everything runs as root by default, unless you use su/sudo in your shell commands to change the user for that particular command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:147
msgid "As such, you should be careful how you set this whole thing up, especially if you plan to give access to (for example) your family, to control home servers and appliances, and so on."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:149
msgid "And again, do not put this on a public server unless you're ready to try and secure the page yourself."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/olivetin.md:150
msgid "Otherwise, have fun with it. It is a neat little tool."
msgstr ""

